Customer Groups

Defining the question

Learn the customers behavior and characteristics and group them.

Defining the metric for success

Being able to sucessfully cluster the customers

Understanding the context

Understanding consumer behavior is a vital aspect of marketing. Consumer behavior is the study of how people make decisions about what they buy, want, need, or act in regards to a product, service, or company. It also helps companies identify opportunities that are not currently met.

Experimental design

  • Problem Definition
  • Data Sourcing
  • Check the Data
  • Perform Data Cleaning
  • Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (Univariate, Bivariate & Multivariate)
  • Implement the Solution
  • Challenge the Solution

Modeling

Heirarchical clustering

#Scale the dataset 
scaled.custm <- scale(custm)
## Calculate the (Euclidean) distances
hist.custm <- dist(scaled.custm)
## Create a hierarchical clustering model
clust.custm <- hclust(hist.custm, method = 'complete')
#Plot (Dendrogram) the clusters to get height 
plot(clust.custm)

## Cut tree so that it has 2 clusters:
custm.clusters <- cutree(clust.custm, k = 2)
# Compare heirarchical cluster to actual clusters
table(custm.clusters)
## custm.clusters
##     1     2 
## 12196     3
table(customer$Revenue)
## 
##     1     2 
## 10291  1908

Hierarchical cluster ,groups 1s as 12196 compared to the actual of 10291 and group 2s as 3 compared to the actual group of 1908

k-means clustering

#Normalization of the data
normal <- function(x) (
  return( ((x - min(x)) /(max(x)-min(x))) )
)
normal(1:18)
##  [1] 0.00000000 0.05882353 0.11764706 0.17647059 0.23529412 0.29411765
##  [7] 0.35294118 0.41176471 0.47058824 0.52941176 0.58823529 0.64705882
## [13] 0.70588235 0.76470588 0.82352941 0.88235294 0.94117647 1.00000000
nom.custm<- as.data.frame(lapply(customer[,-18], normal))
# Create a k-means model on 
custm.km <- kmeans(nom.custm, centers = 2, nstart = 20)
#Plotting the clusters 
plot(custm[c(2,9)], col = custm.km$cluster)

# Compare k Mean cluster to actual clusters
table(custm.km$cluster)
## 
##    1    2 
## 2856 9343
table(customer$Revenue)
## 
##     1     2 
## 10291  1908

K Mean cluster ,groups 1s as 2856 compared to the actual of 10291 and group 2s as 9343 compared to the actual group of 1908

Comparisons between K-Means clustering vs Hierarchical

# Compare hierarchical clustering to k-means
table(custm.clusters)
## custm.clusters
##     1     2 
## 12196     3
table(custm.km$cluster)
## 
##    1    2 
## 2856 9343

Conclusion

K mean clustering performance much better compared to Hierarchical clustering.

  • K mean cluster works better than hierarchical clustering when it come to large datasets , which in our case we had a large dataset.
  • K Means clustering needed advance knowledge of no. of clusters one want to divide your data compared to hierarchical cluster which finds appropriate by interpreting the dendrogram. In our case we have knowledge of the number of clusters.
  • K mean clustering is very sensitive to outliers because when you have outliers, this can affect the average calculation of the whole cluster.
